<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS SING TO REMEMBER 228
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,   Feb.  28  (CNA) 02/28/07  23:16:58 (By Y.C. Jou)
</P>
<P>
Thousands sang in chorus Wednesday afternoon at the heart of
Taipei to remember the 228 Incident of 1947, with President Chen
Shui-bian, former President Lee Teng-hui and several otherPan-
Greencamp political heavyweights present at the rally.
</P>
<P>
The event was held by the Hand-in-Hand to Safeguard Taiwan
Alliance and 228 Incident Memorial Foundation on the Ketagalan
Boulevard in front of the Presidential Office, and opened with an
orchestra's performance of the1947 Overture, a work of composer
Hsiao Tyzen.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the audience, Lee Teng-hui said Taiwan should draw up
a new Constitution, change the country's official name and become
a normal country.
</P>
<P>
Lee said he was a witness and "mental victim" of the 228
Incident, which erupted at the time he was a Taiwan University
senior in agricultural economics.
</P>
<P>
Sixty years on, I still cannot forget the Taiwanese people's
passion to follow their ideals, and the horrible sight of the
Kuomintang slaughtering Taiwanese people,he said.
</P>
<P>
He recited his achievements in curing the wounds caused by the
tragedy during his presidential terms, including setting up a
cabinet level research team to publish an investigative report,
meeting with victims' families, and extending an apology in the
name of the state to people who suffered.
</P>
<P>
President Chen arrived at the event after Lee left and did not
deliver a speech. He sang the songTaiwantogether with the crowd.
</P>
<P>
Ng Chiau-tong, convener of the Hand-in-Hand to Safeguard Taiwan
Alliance, said the 1947 incident happened because Taiwanese
people at that time mistook China as the fatherland, andwe should
never again make the same mistake.
</P>
